    "content_hash": "sha256:d1085e025fe4b8d1e8141eb90e7336db10d2382e1854ba0ca922f6658550c228",
    "summary": "Operation Barbarossa, launched on 22 June 1941, was Germany's invasion of the Soviet Union — the largest land military operation in history — and the decisive theater of [[event:112|World War II]] in terms of scale and casualties. Hitler had always regarded the conquest of Soviet territory as the central objective of his war, seeking Lebensraum (living space) in the east and the destruction of what he called Judeo-Bolshevism. Three Army Groups — North, Centre, and South — advanced simultaneously across a 2,900-kilometer front, deploying approximately three million German soldiers alongside Axis allies from Romania, Hungary, Italy, and Finland.\n\nThe initial months brought staggering German successes. The Soviet military, partly paralyzed by Stalin's purge of experienced officers in the late 1930s and caught partly unprepared despite intelligence warnings, suffered catastrophic defeats. Hundreds of thousands of Soviet troops were encircled and captured at Kiev, Smolensk, Minsk, and other encirclement battles. By autumn 1941, German forces had reached the outskirts of Leningrad and Moscow, and Soviet losses — dead, wounded, and captured — numbered in the millions.\n\nBut the campaign's goals outran its means. Germany had not planned for a campaign extending beyond autumn — Soviet resistance was expected to collapse quickly. The Wehrmacht's logistic system was stretched to breaking point across the vast distances of Russia, and Soviet resistance stiffened as the population responded to what they experienced as an existential war of annihilation. German forces were halted before Moscow in December 1941 by a Soviet counteroffensive launched in temperatures of minus 30 degrees Celsius, for which German troops were catastrophically unprepared. The failure to achieve the expected quick victory transformed the war into the prolonged grinding struggle that ultimately destroyed Germany.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operation_Barbarossa",
